  await db.insert(schema.kbArticlesTable).values([
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-001", title:"ISO 27001:2022 — What Changed from 2013",                    category:"Compliance",      tags:"iso27001,compliance,annex-a",        views:1842, helpful:187, content:"ISO 27001:2022 introduced 11 new controls and merged/revised 58 existing controls, reducing Annex A from 114 to 93 controls across 4 domains (previously 14). Key new controls include threat intelligence (5.7), cloud security (5.23), data masking (8.11), secure coding (8.28) and web filtering (8.23). Organisations certified to the 2013 version had until October 2025 to transition. Gap analysis should focus on new technology and organisational controls not present in the previous version." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-002", title:"SOC 2 Type I vs Type II — What's the Difference",           category:"Compliance",      tags:"soc2,audit,type1,type2",             views:2310, helpful:231, content:"A SOC 2 Type I report assesses whether your security controls are suitably designed at a single point in time. A Type II report tests whether those controls operated effectively over a period (typically 6–12 months). Most enterprise customers require Type II because it provides evidence of sustained control operation. Start with Type I to validate design, then run a 6-month observation period before your Type II audit. Key trust service criteria: Security (CC), Availability (A1), Confidentiality (C1), Processing Integrity (PI1), Privacy (P1-P8)." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-003", title:"Risk Assessment Methodology — ISO 31000 Approach",           category:"Risk Management",  tags:"risk,iso31000,methodology",          views:1521, helpful:156, content:"ISO 31000 defines risk as the effect of uncertainty on objectives. A compliant risk assessment follows: (1) Establish context — define scope, criteria and risk appetite. (2) Risk identification — use STRIDE, threat modelling, asset-based analysis. (3) Risk analysis — assess likelihood × impact to produce inherent risk score. (4) Risk evaluation — compare against appetite thresholds to prioritise. (5) Risk treatment — select Mitigate/Accept/Transfer/Avoid. (6) Monitoring and review — schedule ongoing reassessment. Risk register entries should include risk owner, treatment plan, target residual score and review date." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-004", title:"GDPR Article 17 — Right to Erasure (Right to be Forgotten)", category:"Privacy",         tags:"gdpr,dsar,erasure,privacy",          views:1134, helpful:98,  content:"Article 17 GDPR grants data subjects the right to erasure when: (a) data is no longer necessary for its original purpose; (b) consent is withdrawn; (c) the subject objects and there are no overriding legitimate interests; (d) data was unlawfully processed; (e) erasure is required by EU/Member State law. Organisations must respond within 30 days (extendable by 2 months for complex requests). Erasure does not apply where processing is necessary for legal obligations, public interest, or legal claims. Pseudonymisation is not erasure — all identifying data must be removed or anonymised beyond re-identification." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-005", title:"PCI DSS 4.0 — Key Changes and Customised Approach",          category:"Compliance",      tags:"pcidss,payment,compliance",          views:987,  helpful:89,  content:"PCI DSS 4.0 (effective March 2024) introduced the Customised Approach, allowing organisations to implement alternative controls that meet the intent of a requirement. Key changes: multi-factor authentication now required for all access to the CDE (not just remote access); password complexity increased to 12 characters; phishing-resistant MFA required for privileged accounts; targeted risk analysis introduced for flexible requirements; penetration testing scope expanded to include all system components. All v3.2.1 assessments must transition to v4.0 by March 2025." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-006", title:"Conducting a Business Impact Analysis (BIA)",                  category:"Business Continuity", tags:"bcp,bia,continuity,rto,rpo",       views:876,  helpful:82,  content:"A Business Impact Analysis identifies critical business functions and quantifies the impact of their disruption over time. BIA process: (1) Identify all business processes and assign owners. (2) For each process, assess financial, operational, reputational and regulatory impact across 4 time horizons: 1h, 4h, 24h, 72h. (3) Determine Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD). (4) Define Recovery Time Objective (RTO — target restoration time) and Recovery Point Objective (RPO — acceptable data loss). (5) Identify critical dependencies: people, technology, third parties. (6) Present findings to senior management and integrate into BCP and DR plans." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-007", title:"Cloud Security Posture Management (CSPM) Explained",          category:"Cloud Security",   tags:"cspm,cloud,aws,azure,gcp",           views:1654, helpful:163, content:"CSPM continuously monitors cloud infrastructure configurations against security benchmarks (CIS, NIST, vendor best practice). Key capabilities: (1) Asset discovery — auto-inventory of all cloud resources across accounts/subscriptions. (2) Misconfiguration detection — compare actual config against policy (e.g., S3 bucket not public, encryption enabled). (3) Compliance mapping — map findings to ISO 27001, SOC 2, PCI DSS controls. (4) Drift detection — alert when config deviates from approved baseline. (5) Remediation guidance — step-by-step fix instructions. MTTR for critical CSPM findings should be <24h. Integrate CSPM findings with your GRC risk register for full-loop management." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-008", title:"Zero Trust Architecture — Core Principles",                   category:"Security Architecture", tags:"zerotrust,iam,network,identity",   views:2198, helpful:214, content:"Zero Trust operates on 'never trust, always verify'. Core principles: (1) Verify explicitly — authenticate and authorise every request using all available data points (identity, location, device health, service/workload, data classification, anomalies). (2) Use least privilege — limit access with JIT/JEA, risk-based adaptive policies and data protection. (3) Assume breach — minimise blast radius, segment access, encrypt end-to-end, use analytics to get visibility, drive threat detection and improve defences. NIST SP 800-207 provides the reference architecture. Implementation pillars: identity, endpoints, applications, data, infrastructure, networks." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-009", title:"How to Write an Effective Information Security Policy",         category:"Governance",       tags:"policy,governance,iso27001",         views:765,  helpful:71,  content:"An effective information security policy should: (1) State purpose and scope — what it covers and who it applies to. (2) Reference senior management commitment. (3) Define information security objectives aligned to business goals. (4) Include definitions of key terms. (5) Assign responsibilities — CISO, managers, all staff. (6) State consequences of non-compliance. (7) Reference supporting standards and procedures. Avoid being overly technical — policies are intent documents; procedures contain the 'how'. Review annually or after significant changes. Version control with effective and review dates is mandatory for ISO 27001 compliance. Keep to 2–4 pages; use appendices for supporting detail." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-010", title:"Vulnerability Management — Prioritisation with CVSS and EPSS", category:"Vulnerability",    tags:"cvss,epss,vulnmgt,patching",         views:1432, helpful:141, content:"CVSS (Common Vulnerability Scoring System) v3.1 provides a severity score 0–10 (None/Low/Medium/High/Critical) based on exploitability and impact. Limitation: CVSS scores severity in isolation — it does not reflect actual exploitation probability. EPSS (Exploit Prediction Scoring System) predicts the probability a vulnerability will be exploited in the next 30 days. Best practice: combine CVSS + EPSS for prioritisation. Focus patching effort on: (1) CVSS Critical (9.0+) AND EPSS >10%: patch within 24h. (2) CVSS High (7.0–8.9) AND EPSS >5%: patch within 7 days. (3) CVSS Critical/High with EPSS <1%: patch within 30 days. CISA KEV (Known Exploited Vulnerabilities) should always be P1." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-011", title:"NIST Cybersecurity Framework 2.0 — Overview",                  category:"Compliance",       tags:"nist,csf,framework,governance",      views:1876, helpful:182, content:"NIST CSF 2.0 (published February 2024) added a new 'Govern' function to the original five (Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover). The Govern function covers: organisational context, risk management strategy, cybersecurity supply chain risk management, roles/responsibilities, policy and oversight. CSF 2.0 broadened scope from critical infrastructure to all organisations. Key resource: CSF 2.0 Profiles allow organisations to document their current and target cybersecurity posture. CSF 2.0 Tiers (1–4: Partial, Risk Informed, Repeatable, Adaptive) assess maturity. The framework is freely available at nist.gov/cyberframework." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-012", title:"Incident Response Playbook — Ransomware",                      category:"Incident Response", tags:"ransomware,ir,playbook,containment",  views:2890, helpful:289, content:"Ransomware Response: DETECT — Monitor for encryption telemetry, EDR alerts, unusually high file modification rates. CONTAIN (within 30 minutes) — Network isolate affected hosts; revoke compromised credentials; block C2 IPs/domains at firewall and DNS. ASSESS — Identify patient zero; determine ransomware family via sample analysis; check decryptor availability (nomoreransom.org). NOTIFY — CEO/Board within 2h; legal team; cyber insurer; regulators if PII involved (GDPR: 72h). RECOVER — Restore from immutable backups; verify clean state before reconnecting; do NOT pay ransom without legal/insurer consultation. POST-INCIDENT — Root cause analysis; lessons learned; update detection rules and playbook." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-013", title:"Data Classification Framework — Four-Tier Model",               category:"Data Protection",  tags:"data,classification,dlp,privacy",    views:934,  helpful:87,  content:"A four-tier data classification model: (1) PUBLIC — Information approved for public release. No access controls required. Examples: press releases, public website content. (2) INTERNAL — Business information for employee use only. Basic access controls. Examples: internal policies, org charts. (3) CONFIDENTIAL — Sensitive business information. Role-based access, encryption in transit and at rest. Examples: contracts, financial reports, personal data. (4) RESTRICTED — Highest sensitivity. Strict need-to-know, encryption everywhere, audit logging. Examples: PII/PCI data, credentials, IP. DLP policy should enforce classification at creation; automated scanning should detect misclassified data." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-014", title:"Third Party Risk Management — Vendor Tiering",                  category:"Risk Management",  tags:"tprm,vendor,thirdparty,risk",        views:1120, helpful:109, content:"Vendor tiering focuses risk management effort on highest-impact relationships. Tier 1 (Critical): vendors with direct access to PII, payment data or core systems; single-source dependencies; vendors processing >10K records. Assessment: annual comprehensive questionnaire + on-site review + continuous monitoring. Tier 2 (Important): SaaS applications, cloud infrastructure, professional services. Assessment: annual SIG Lite questionnaire + evidence review. Tier 3 (Standard): low-impact vendors, no data access. Assessment: self-attestation every 2 years. Minimum requirements for all tiers: signed DPA, security questionnaire, right-to-audit clause in contract, GDPR standard contractual clauses for international transfers." },
    { tenantId, articleId:"KB-015", title:"MFA Best Practices and Phishing-Resistant Authentication",       category:"Identity & Access",  tags:"mfa,authentication,phishing,fido2",  views:1567, helpful:154, content:"MFA significantly reduces account takeover risk but not all MFA is equal. Phishing-resistant MFA (PCI DSS 4.0 requirement for privileged access): FIDO2/WebAuthn hardware keys (YubiKey, Google Titan) — strongest protection; device-bound passkeys (platform authenticator) — strong, no separate hardware needed. Phishable MFA (avoid for privileged accounts): SMS OTP — SIM-swap vulnerable; email OTP — account compromise risk; TOTP apps — real-time phishing possible. Deployment guidance: (1) Enforce MFA for all admin/privileged access immediately. (2) Roll out to all users with TOTP minimum. (3) For high-risk roles, upgrade to FIDO2. (4) Monitor for MFA fatigue attacks (multiple push notifications); implement number matching." },
  ]).onConflictDoNothing();
